===Etymology===
From Greek ''[[θαυματουργία]]'', from ''[[θαύμα]]'' ‘miracle, wonder’ + ''[[-εργος]]'' ‘working’.

===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|/ˈθɔ:mətɜ:ʤi/}} (''[[RP]]'')
*{{IPA|/ˈθɒməˌtərʤɪ/}} (''US'')
*{{audio|en-us-thaumaturgy.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|thaumaturgies}}

# The working of [[miracle]]s
# [[magic|Magic]]; [[witchcraft]], [[wizardry]]

====Quotations====
;the working of miracles (1)
*'''1898''' — [[w:H. G. Wells|H. G. Wells]], ''[[s:The Man Who Could Work Miracles|The Man Who Could Work Miracles]]''
*:There were astonishing changes. The small hours found Mr. Maydig and Mr. Fotheringay careering across the chilly market square under the still moon, in a sort of ecstasy of '''thaumaturgy''', Mr. Maydig all flap and gesture, Mr. Fotheringay short and bristling, and no longer abashed at his greatness

